fields.question: How do I get over there?
fields.answer: Comment est-ce que je fais pour aller là-bas ?

fields.question: My bike was recently stolen
fields.answer: On a récemment volé mon vélo

fields.question: How are you?
fields.answer:
Comment allez-vous ?

Culture Note: We have different ways to say "how are you" in French, from the informal ça va? to the more formal comment allez- vous? When talking to strangers in France, we always use the vous form.

fields.question: Don't mention it
fields.answer:
Il n'y a pas de quoi

Culture Note: French people speak so fast they often say y'a pas d'quoi. Parisians are especially known to speak very fast and "eat" their words when a sentence is long! Here, il n'y a pas de quoi could literally translate into "there is not anything" (to thank me for).

fields.question: in spring
fields.answer:
au printemps

Grammar Note: Did you answer en printemps? You were almost correct! All months and seasons in French are preceded by en, except for spring! "In spring" is au printemps.

fields.question: in July
fields.answer:
au mois de juillet

Grammar Note: In front of the months, it is common to use either en or au mois de to say "in." Let's use this in the following couple of lines.

fields.question: Well...
fields.answer:
Bon...

Grammar Note: Now we have the opposite of what we saw previously: when used in the beginning of a sentence, bon, which actually means "good," corresponds to "Well..." in English.

fields.question: Vado a mangiare
fields.answer:
Je mangerai

In francese "Aller + Verbo nell'infinito" è un modo di esprimere un futuro immediato, e spesso può essere sostituito da un futuro semplice. In ogni caso, questo ha spesso il significato di un semplice futuro, ma lo usiamo per facilità

fields.question: dove
fields.answer:
où

Grammar Note: Ou means "or," and où means "where." The only difference is the little accent on the "u" when it means "where." That's why the accents are so important in written French: they can completely change the meaning of a word!

fields.question: Sorry, I don't understand English
fields.answer:
Désolée, je ne comprends pas l'anglais

Grammar Note: Careful! When we use parler, "to speak," we can simply say the language name, like anglais in Je parle anglais. But with other verbs like comprendre, you have to use "the" in front of the language name. You'll literally be saying something like "I understand THE English." Remember that you need to use the correct form of "the" according to the gender of anglais, which is masculine.

Grammar Note: Did you notice the extra "e" at the end of désolée when a woman says it? That's the mark of the feminine form in French.

fields.question: I speak French very well
fields.answer:
Je parle très bien français

Grammar Note: Did you say je parle français très bien? Careful, "very well" goes right after the verb in French.

fields.question: No, I am from France
fields.answer:
Non, je viens de France

Grammar Note: Did you figure out the pattern? We don't use articles before a feminine country name in French when we use de (from). So we say je viens de France. Remember also, if the country is masculine and begins with le then we use du (je viens du Japon). If it is plural, we use des (Je viens des États- Unis).

fields.question: Nice to meet you!
fields.answer:
Enchantée !

Grammar Note: Remember, in French, we put an extra "e" at the end of words when a woman says it. That's the mark of the feminine in French. So, here it is enchantée when Marie says it and enchanté when Christophe says it. But as you can hear, they are both pronounced the same way.

fields.question: No, she's not French, she's Portuguese
fields.answer:
Non, elle n'est pas française, elle est portugaise

Grammar Note: When you use the extra "- e" for the feminine form, it changes the pronunciation as well. It sounds as if there's a "z" at the end: Portugais/ Portugaise, Français/ Française.

Grammar Note: When ne is in front of a verb beginning with a vowel, ne becomes n', as in elle n'est pas, to avoid an awkward pronunciation.

fields.question: I am a salesperson
fields.answer:
Je suis vendeur

Grammar Note: When describing your occupation, you do not use the article in front of the profession. For example, "I am a dentist" will become je suis dentiste.

fields.question: what, which
fields.answer:
quel

Grammar Note: Quel is an interrogative adjective; this means that you will only use it when asking a question. Like other adjectives, it agrees with the noun that follows so it can be masculine, feminine, singular or plural. In the question "What is your address?", "what" refers to "the address," which is feminine in French. Most of the time, you need to add an - e to the adjective to make it feminine. But quel is irregular and it becomes quelle.

fields.question: I live on Napoleon street
fields.answer:
J'habite rue Napoléon

Grammar Note: French uses prepositions a lot. But whenever you describe which street you live on, you should omit "on."

fields.question: I live at 7 Napoleon street
fields.answer:
J'habite au 7 rue Napoléon

Grammar Note: While you do not need a preposition when you mention the street you live on, if you add the house number, you do need to use au.

fields.question: eleven (11)  twelve (12)  thirteen (13)
fields.answer:
onze (11)

douze (12)

treize (13)

Grammar Note: Can you see a pattern forming? Knowing that numbers 11 to 16 all end in - ze might help you to memorize them.

fields.question: I am thirty-one years old
fields.answer:
J'ai trente-et-un ans

Grammar Note: It is quite easy to form numbers in French, but watch out for et- un! 21 is vingt- et- un, you are literally saying twenty- and- one. It is the same for 31 trente- et- un, 41 quarante- et- un, 51 cinquante- et- un and 61 soixante- et- un. For other numbers, just add deux, trois, quatre, cinq, six, sept, huit, and neuf to your number like in English. For example 46 is quarante- six. After 69, things get a bit tricky. Are you ready?

fields.question: seventy-nine (79)
fields.answer:
soixante- dix- neuf (70)

Grammar Note: Can you see a pattern emerging? 79 will be soixante- dix- neuf (you are literally saying "sixty- nineteen").

fields.question: eighty-seven (87)
fields.answer:
quatre-vingt-sept (87)

Grammar Note: Have you noticed the difference between quatre- vingts and quatre- vingt- sept? When you say quatre- vingts (eighty), vingt takes an - s. But the - s disappears as soon as it is followed by a numeral adjective, for example 83 is quatre- vingt- trois but 80 million is quatre- vingts millions.

fields.question: Tuesday March 1st
fields.answer:
mardi premier mars

Grammar Note: Just like in English, for every first day of the month, we use "first," premier but for the second, the third, the fourth, and so on of the month, we just say two, three, four, etc. In written French, the abbreviation for "first" is 1er. The construction of the date is also a bit different from English. In French, we say day/date/month, mardi premier mars.

fields.question: we are
fields.answer:
on est

Grammar Note: In French, we have two ways to translate "we": nous and on. On is a bit more informal but used a lot in spoken French. The trick is that although it means "we," grammatically we use the singular form of the verb, or the il/elle form!

fields.question: Today is Thursday December 6th
fields.answer:
Aujourd'hui on est le jeudi six décembre

Grammar Note: Like in English, when talking about the date in the month we add le (the). For example, le mercredi neuf is "Wednesday the 9th." But unlike English, we still add le when we include the month: le mercredi neuf décembre (Wednesday 9th December).

fields.question: It is March 15th today, isn't it?
fields.answer:
C'est le 15 mars aujourd'hui, n'est-ce pas ?

Grammar Note: N'est- ce pas is not only used to say "isn't it?". You can use it in all sentences regardless of the verb and the tense of the sentence. So it can also mean "haven't you?", "aren't you?", "didn't you" and so on. So easy, n'est- ce pas?

fields.question: My favorite color is white
fields.answer:
Ma couleur préférée est le blanc

Grammar Note: Colors, when used as a noun, are masculine. Whenever you use a color as a noun, you should always have an article in front of it. Can you remember the masculine form of "the"? Let's try to use it now.

fields.question: the grape
fields.answer:
le raisin

Grammar Note: Cognates are words that are very similar in two languages and have the same meaning, like "soup" and soupe. There are also faux- amis (false friends), like raisin. Raisin means "grape," and "raisin" in English is raisin sec (dried grape) in French!

Questa t si usa alla forma interrogativa, quando il verbo finisce con una vocale e con i pronomi il, elle, on.

elle s'appelle Lisa / s'appelle-t-elle Lisa ?

il prendra du vin / prendra-t-il du vin ? (futuro)

on mange / mange-t-on ?

Ma

il prend / prend-il?

on est / est-on ?

ils mangent / mangent-ils ?

tu nages bien / nages-tu bien?

fields.question: sopra

dessus

Sur, dessus, au-dessus, au dessus-de

sur è sempre seguito da qualcosa, di solito un articolo e un nome:

La bouteille est sur la table.

Le chat dort sur le lit.

Je suis assise sur l'herbe.

Petits bateaux sur l'eau....

Non si può dire La bouteille est sur

Quando un oggetto è sur un altro c'è contatto tra i due oggetti. La lampe est sur la table significa che la lampada è posata sul tavolo.

Ma per il sole, si può dire sur, anche se non c'è contatto tra il sole e la terra !

Il y a un beau soleil sur les Alpes.

fields.question: It's ridiculous to be afraid of being ridiculous!
fields.answer:
C'est ridicule d'avoir peur d'être ridicule !

Why is there a "d'" after "ridicule" here? I get it after "peur" but I don't understand its usage after "ridicule"

-> Most adjectives need "de" before an infinitive.

fields.question: The actor who acts in this play doesn't know how to act well
fields.answer:
L'acteur qui joue dans cette pièce de théâtre ne sait pas bien jouer

-> "bien" comes very often before the verb it describes. "Bien joué" is even an idiom to say "good game". To say "not knowing well" we'd put it this way "Il ne sait pas bien comment jouer" (= how to act).

fields.question: I eat all the time
fields.answer:
Je mange tout le temps

I get so confused as to when to use tout and tous!

-> "Tout" is an adjective, so it shouldn't be too unfamiliar:

-> tout is used before a masculine singular noun (tout le temps)

-> toute is used before a feminine singular noun (toute la famille)

-> tous is used before a masculine plural noun (tous les jours)

-> toutes is used before a feminine plural noun (toutes les filles)

-> Temps appears plural but its singular meaning 'time'. And its le temps...... Hence tout le temps

fields.question: Who is your favorite actress?
fields.answer:
Qui est ton actrice préférée ?

-> Isn't it "ta actrice préférée"?

-> French hates having two vowels sounds next to each other as in 'ta actrice'. So instead it inserts a consonant in between, making it 'ton actrice'. That's also the reason why it's 'cet hôtel' and not 'ce hôtel' and why the end of the ils/elles conjugation of verbs sometimes is sounded.

fields.question: We're going to visit our family
fields.answer:
Nous allons rendre visite à notre famille

-> Is "Nous allons visiter notre famille" really wrong?

-> In french you would rather use visiter + direct object for a place (a museum, a country...) and not for people.

-> If anyone wants to know whether to use "ser" or "estar" with soltero (which to me is not a permanent state so I would lean toward using "estar"), here's what I found on wordreference:

Él es soltero = Nunca ha contraído matrimonio - Él está soltero = ha estado casado pero ahora no lo está.
